requirements:
MCU- Metropolitan Congregations United seeks a St. Louis based Energy Benchmarking Intern with a wide range of administrative, organizational, communication, and technical skills to assist with our regional voluntary energy benchmarking efforts with faith-based organizations within our environmental justice organizing campaign. The Energy Benchmarking Internship will be of interest to students in technical, engineering, architectural, or scientific programs, as well as students in urban planning and environmental programs. The position reports to the MCU Lead Environmental Justice Organizer.

The primary responsibilities of the Energy Benchmarking Intern are to:
Assist MCU’s Environmental Justice Campaign Staff with outreach to develop strong relationships with local congregations, clergy leaders, and residents of color throughout North County and North City utilizing basic relational organizing tools. Training will be provided.
Assist with providing presentations and education workshops to encourage congregation participation in the voluntary benchmarking campaign.
Assist congregation building owners with the process of benchmarking their buildings in ENERGY STAR Portfolio Manager, which will include working with staff to collect building energy and water data, property use details needed for benchmarking, setting up properties in Portfolio Manager, and setting up a process so municipalities can be successful with continued benchmarking in the future. Training to use ENERGY STAR Portfolio Manager will be provided.
Maintain consistent communication with MCU Environmental Justice Campaign Staff and the Interfaith Environmental Justice Task Force about activities and regularly attending meetings.
 The following qualifications are desired but not required:
·      Experience connecting with black communities and congregations is highly valued;
·      Fluency in racial equity issues, implicit bias, dialogues around race and public policy;
·      Strong understanding and passion for social justice and environmental justice issues;
·      Experience with issues surrounding energy use, transportation, utilities, and/or solid waste;
·      Strong oral and communication skills critical for working with a variety of community leaders and personalities;
·      Ability to work independently and take initiative to accomplish goals;
·      Proficiency in computer skills (Microsoft Office, Google Drive, video chat software, and specifically data analysis/manipulation using Excel or other software); and
·      Ability to work at least 10 hours per week, during some evenings, and weekend events;
·      Special consideration will be given to candidates from the targeted communities.
 LOCATION: This internship is expected to be mainly remote, with periodic socially distanced, masked, brief in-person activities. Local travel to community meetings may be required. Regular communications with your supervisor will occur by phone and video.
 COMPENSATION: A stipend of $500/month is provided for up to 4 months during a semester.
 HOURS: 130 total hours between February and May are expected but can be flexible. Specific hourly schedules are determined by the intern and their supervisor.
 TO APPLY: Please apply by sending a cover letter and resume. In the cover letter, please highlight your interest in the internship and your most relevant experience. Please also include details about any leadership roles you have had.

For more information on MCU- Metropolitan Congregations United, visit www.mcustl.com.

Business Unit Description

AARP is a nonprofit, nonpartisan organization, with a membership of nearly 38 million that helps people turn their goals and dreams into 'Real Possibilities' by changing the way America defines aging. With staffed offices in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands, AARP works to strengthen communities and promote the issues that matter most to families such as healthcare security, financial security and personal fulfillment. AARP also advocates for individuals in the marketplace by selecting products and services of high quality and value to carry the AARP name. As a trusted source for news and information, AARP produces the world’s largest circulation magazine, AARP The Magazine and AARP Bulletin.

Summary

This North Dakota-based internship (virtual until further notice) will provide the student the opportunity to participate in a broad range of activities and events focused on issues of importance to people 50-plus and their families in North Dakota. Our priorities have been identified and will include work on fraud prevention, retirement readiness, healthy living and building volunteer power. The intern will learn different web-based tools AARP uses to communicate with its members and others, including but not limited to Brightspot, Sprinklr, and Microsoft Office products.

Responsibilities

This internship will run from May-August 2021, requiring the intern to work up to 40 hours per week. Specific tasks include
Assist with volunteer engagement around virtual events;
Assist in building out local advocacy efforts with local elected officials and partners and establish volunteer cadres;
Assist with AARP North Dakota’s social media accounts to including an emphasis on video capture and production around priority issue areas;
Write draft stories for the state webpage, news releases, newsletter stories, social media posts, and emails to members and volunteers;
Prepare materials for legislators and volunteers on AARP positions on priority issues and assist with monitoring legislative committee meetings as needed;
Assist in preparing public/volunteer educational materials using Publisher, PowerPoint, Prezi or other electronic tools;
Assist in keeping volunteers and members informed of organizational developments and opportunities to engage;
Requirements

Interns must be currently enrolled in a degreed program at an accredited college or university; and be considered rising undergraduate juniors or seniors, graduate students, or post doctorate students.

AARP also considers non-traditional interns who are looking to re-enter the workforce or change careers. This may include those who have previously graduated college and are now enrolled in a continuing education program.
Benefits Offered

Internships are non-exempt positions and are not eligible for employee benefits.

At AARP, the health and well-being of our candidates, employees, and members is a top priority. As a result of the COVID pandemic, all interviews will be held virtually and all non-essential employees will continue to work remotely until further notice. AARP has established social distancing policies to ensure the safety of our essential employees.
Equal Employment Opportunity

AARP is an equal opportunity employer committed to hiring a diverse workforce and sustaining an inclusive culture. AARP does not discriminate on the basis of race, ethnicity, religion, sex, color, national origin, age, sexual orientation, gender identity or expression, mental or physical disability, genetic information, veteran status, or on any other basis prohibited by applicable law.
